[1]
Date: Tue 28 Jan 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Press and Journal, Tue 28 Jan 2003 [edited]
<http://www.thisisnorthscotland.co.uk>

Scotland: outbreaks in Aberdeen hospitals and schools
-----------------------------------------------------
A second ward at Aberdeen Royal Infirmary (ARI) has been closed after being
hit by the winter vomiting disease virus. It was confirmed yesterday that
38 people have been affected, resulting in the closure of one of the
hospital's wards on Fri 24 Jan 2003. The decision to shut it down was made
prior to the first ward to be affected reopening over the weekend.
An ARI spokeswoman said: "In total, 26 patients and 12 staff have been
affected over a 3 ward area. "Throughout the whole of ARI we do have
sporadic outbreaks of illness during the course of the year. These closures
do not have an adverse effect on any patients." She added that reports of
several more cases than usual at Woodend Hospital were also being
investigated. Meanwhile, no new cases of [viral gastroenteritis] have been
reported at the city's Rosewell House care home. At Stonehaven Community
Hospital, only one patient is still suffering from [viral gastroenteritis].
The hospital's Arduthie ward, which had been closed due to the illness, was
reopened yesterday.
The outbreak of [viral gastroenteritis] started 2 weeks ago. A public
health team and Aberdeen City Council's environmental health department are
investigating the cause and nature of the [infection], and results are
expected in the next 2 to 3 weeks. Schoolchildren throughout the north east
have also been struck down by [suspected winter vomiting disease]. As many
as 700 pupils are believed to have suffered from the flu-like virus over
the last few weeks. Westhill Academy reported that as many as 200 of its
909 students have been off ill in the last 2 weeks.
Other schools whose attendance levels were hit include Portlethen Academy,
Harlaw Academy, and Aberdeen Grammar School. Yesterday, a spokeswoman for
the council said she was unable to confirm how many youngsters had been
absent due to the illness.
[byline: Laura Grant]
[As inferred previously (see preceding update), the outbreak of suspected
viral gastroenteritis affecting schools and hospitals in Aberdeen is being
attributed to norovirus infection. Laboratory confirmation of the diagnosis
is awaited. - Mod.CP]
