USA: Norovirus outbreaks in 4 Michigan nursing homes
----------------------------------------------------
At least 4 area nursing homes have experienced recent outbreaks of
norovirus infection. Within a day, the virus infection made half of a
nursing home's residents ill and caused staff to miss work, said Priya
Nair, epidemiologist for the Genesee County Health Department "When it
happens, it's hard to prevent transmission," Nair said. "The virus can be
airborne and easily spread by touch, but they've done their best to reduce
risks like canceling communal events."
Nair has helped investigate the outbreaks since November [2002]. The latest
one was last week at a nursing home with 134 residents. 60 per cent of the
residents fell ill, and 20 per cent of the staff were sick, she said.
Cruise ships, like nursing homes, harbor the virus among people who are in
continuously close contact. In addition, the elderly have a lower
resistance to illness, Nair said.
South east Michigan has seen 20 outbreaks of noroviruses, or Norwalk-like
viruses, a group of viruses that cause acute gastroenteritis, said Geralyn
Lasher, spokeswoman for the Michigan Department of Community Health.
Officials at the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
announced that noroviruses appear to be on the rise. But after the cruise
problems in the fall, people are paying more attention to what's causing
gastrointestinal problems. "There's more awareness of it," Lasher said.
"Health care providers are taking the time to do testing instead of writing
it off as a general gastrointestinal [infection]." The current strain of
norovirus in Genesee County is called the Farmington Hills strain because
it was identified there in April 2002, Nair said.
[byline: Shantell M Kirkendoll]
[See ProMED-mail post archived as "Norovirus activity 2002 - USA
20030123.0206" for a more detailed description of the Farmington Hills
strain. - Mod.CP]
